The paper deals with logical fragments and their closure properties over finite words, which suggests that it belongs to the Formal Languages and Automata Theory (cs.FL) sub-category. The paper also discusses lattice structures and morphisms, which are topics commonly studied in the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category. The use of closure properties and the investigation of certain restrictions of logic formulae suggest that the paper may also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper also presents examples of fragments that capture certain properties of languages, which suggests that it may belong to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the expressive power of certain fragments, which is a topic commonly studied in the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category.
